post_text: New this year! Every High School student has a Naviance account. Naviance is a platform NEAAAT is using to help students to gain college and career knowledge. It‚Äôs a tool to help students learn about their strengths and interests and match them to colleges and careers. Students will manage their SMART Goals, have access to SAT and ACT Prep, and during students senior year, it will help streamline the college admissions process by linking the Naviance account with college applications.

post_text: Congratulations to Erin Wooten on her acceptance at The Culinary Institute of Virginia. The Culinary Institute of Virginia is located in Norfolk and is a part of the ECPI University. They offer degrees in both culinary arts and baking and pastry. Erin plans on taking the baking and pastry degree program, which will have classes such as "bread baking" and "cake decorating." After earning her degree, she hope to get a job in a higher end area such as a cruise ship or Disney resort.

Open Houses and "Meet and Greet" Town Halls

Unfortunately, we'll be unable to hold our full Open House events as we have in the past; however, we've put together a few opportunities for students, parents, and staff to get to know one another prior to the first day of school.

We'll kick off these events with Grade Level Town Halls. Please join our coaches at the dates and times shown below to meet our coaches, learn about expectations and procedures, and pose questions for our teams to answer. Specific contact information for each town hall will be communicated next week. We look forward to seeing you soon!

5th Grade: Wednesday, 8/12, 7:00pm

6th Grade: Wednesday, 8/12, 6:00pm

7th Grade: Thursday, 8/13, 6:00pm

8th Grade: Wednesday, 8/12, 6:00pm

High School: Tuesday, 8/11, 6:30pm

UPDATE OF PREVIOUS POSTING: The Drone Certification Exam is $160.00

This is an exciting opportunity with our STEM partners NineTen Drones and STEMERALD City! NEAAAT students must be 16 years of age before taking the certification exam. The course and training are free, but there is a $160.00 certification exam fee.
We hope to have enough drone certified students to start a drone club during the 2020-2021 school year.
Please email Dr. Tonya Little, Executive Director of STEM, at tonyalittle@northeastacademy.org for more information.

Please email Dr. Tonya Little, Executive Director of STEM, at tonyalittle@northeastacademy.org for more information.

FREE Remote Summer Opportunity for Girls, Current 4th-8th Graders

Now more than ever, people are searching for ways to stay connected and to stay active. Schools across the country are closed, and it can feel like life has been put on pause. In response to the COVID-19 pandemic, Envision Lead Grow wants girls everywhere to know that becoming a boss never stops. ELG 2.0: Virtual Immersion will allow girls to learn what it takes to become an entrepreneur in the comfort of their homes while connecting with girls across the country! Our mission is to increase the rate of entrepreneurship for girls throughout the United States. When you become an ELG girl boss, you will have access to the four parts of our scholarship program, starting with our week-long virtual immersion.
https://envisionleadgrow.org/elg-2-0-virtual-immersion/

post_text: Final Day of Texas Instruments-Innovator Training: Coding a Pet Alarm! NEAAAT Coaches Cahoon (Math), McPherson (Coding), Turner (Math) and Gibson (Math) have spent four days discovering how to integrate STEM learning with TI- Innovator calculators, sensors and tools. Today they programmed a Pet Car Alarm. When temperatures increase, an alarm sounds, windows roll down, and the car lights flash! Rescue the ‚Äúpet‚Äù in the vehicle! Real-world learning, solving authentic problems!

Reflection of the 2020 Remote Learning at NEAAAT. These past 2 1/2 months have tested the resilience, adaptability, flexibility, creativity, critical thinking, and communication skills that we value, grow, and uphold as a NEAAAT community. We hope that you have a good summer. The lessons we have learned from the challenges you faced during the spring semester will serve all of us well as we move forward in a very different world. Be confident in your ability to walk through unexpected or unplanned doors of opportunity. In the words of Albert Einstein, "In the middle of difficulty lies opportunity."

At the end of this reflection, Coach Philip Garrett Huey gives a special tribute to the Class of 2020!
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=u-QS9FORC1A&t=70s

post_text:
Senior Shout Out!
Highlighting our Senior Griffins, the fabulous Class of 2020!

"I am one of the original NEAAAT students that helped found the school, year one.I am an Eagle Scout, and I am graduating COA with an Associate's Degree in Science in two weeks, but graduation isn't until July because of the pandemic. I have been accepted to Virginia Wesleyan University as a Merit Scholarship recipient, as of today, and plan to graduate with my BS in Earth and Environmental Science/Biology and certify to teach middle grades and high school science. I plan to be the first graduate of NEAAAT to return to NEAAAT and carry on the traditions of PBL and Pi Day that we established since the beginning. I hope to return to mentor the FRC team and support the program I have been part of these past 2 1/2 years. Being Captain of FRC this year meant everything to me and I want to give back what the program gave me: Confidence, knowledge, teamwork skills, laughter, and lifelong friendships." - Christopher West

post_text:
From Coach Deborah West : Students in Biotech are working on a presentation to entice "Travel Corp" to hire their agricultural biotech company to feed the colonists on Mars from food that can be regrown from scraps, or harvested while continuing to grow. Today's task was to provide a single-meal plan/recipe that can be used to show off your products. I expected a brief listing, a recipe, a drawing, etc to get the point across as they prepare for Friday. I have seen salads, stews, baked potatoes, an omelet, guacamole, but nothing like this.

Riley Sisson, a 6th-grade student has gone above and beyond today. I hope you enjoy this as much as I did. Now, I want a salad.

April 2 at 3:49 PM ¬∑

Friends and family,

While dealing with loss is always challenging, it is especially difficult to do so during a time in which we cannot be together. With this in mind, please tune in to Dixie 105.7 this Saturday, April 4th at 10:30 AM. A special tribute is going to be paid to Damari. Let's all blast the song and sing along to remember his amazingness, and let he and his family know how loved they are during this time. shared_text:
Jessa Kimbra Trotman
March 30 at 1:55 AM ¬∑

I crazily stopped you in Muddy‚Äôs parking lot one day and asked if I could draw you. I snapped some photos, you smiled. You didn‚Äôt even know how iconic you were. You would ride past our shop everyday, balancing, texting not even looking where you were going. You had EC all mapped out. I wanted to be like you. You were so cool in your own world. We screamed and smiled so hard when you rode by in the Christmas parade. I wish I stopped you more and talked to you.
Our city isn‚Äôt the same without you.

Love on your children.
Check on them and talk to them- even if you have to dig. My heart is hurting tonight.

post_text: Every day, we can't wait to see what mug is coming off the wall, and the story of the artist and design process associated with it. In Coach Caitlin K. McDonald's class today we learned more about slipcasting, slip trailing, 3D printing used to make mugs, and much more. We would've never had the opportunity to see this wonderful wall of unique artistry if it were not for Coach McDonald's coaching from home. Thank you, Coach McDonald, for sharing your artistry with us. Our students are very fortunate to have you as a Design Thinking Coach!

McDonald is checking in with her Design Thinking students. She is sharing her collection of cups, seen behind her, featuring a cup at each session and sharing information about the artist.

post_text:
Pasquotank County: In partnership with ECPPS and Albemarle Food Bank, meals will be available for students ages 1-18, or still enrolled in K-12 schools. Exceptional Children students are eligible up to age 22. NEAAAT students can go to any of the schools providing meals and obtain a meal. Meals are available for all students, regardless of economic status. Students do not have to receive free or reduced meals to be eligible. ALL students are eligible. We are working together to meet the needs of our students and families.

Chowan County: Lunch is available for pick-up from 12 - 1 at John A. Holmes High and Chowan Middle.

Perquimans County: School feeding sites will be from 11:00 to 1:00 at Perquimans Central School and Hertford Grammar School.

Camden: Camden plans to start "grab and go" food services for students on Monday, March 23rd at the Grandy Primary School cafeteria 11:30AM - 1:00PM (Monday - Friday).

post_text:
Because our school is located on the campus of ECSU, we remain in close contact with our partners at ECSU and their advisement from the UNC General Administration, we'll be collaborating over the next few days to determine if any additional measures may be necessary for NEAAAT. Among these measures is to limit large groups of people in close proximity while on university campuses, including ECSU. In an effort to honor the University of North Carolina system‚Äôs mandate and cooperate with our partner, ECSU, several NEAAAT events have been postponed.

Unfortunately, we are postponing all events scheduled for the remaining dates of March 2020. Unfortunately, the Delta Academy/Delta GEMS Women's History Month Tea will be postponed. We are currently working with ECSU to reschedule our March events. We are looking to reschedule the Delta Academy/Delta GEMS High Tea in May.

We appreciate your understanding and support as we continue to navigate this public health issue together. We will notify the public of the rescheduled date.

Who knew that out of this grant we would develop a market study?
